es":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring this stage, there is extensive formation of secondary septa which subdivide the primitive air spaces into mature alveoli. The process begins at approximately 36 weeks gestation and continues postnatally. At birth, there are approximately 50 million alveoli, and this number increases to around 300 million by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompletion at age eight years.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis prolonged developmental period explains why children have significant capacity for lung growth and repair compared to adults, where alveolar regeneration is limited.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The alveolar stage of lung development occurs from 36 weeks gestation to eight years of age.","During respiratory system development secondary septation creates mature alveoli during the alveolar stage.","The number of alveoli increases from 50 million at birth to 300 million by age eight."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T11:27:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T11:28:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63247"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c